## Bug

In `platform/plugin-sdk/src/dom.ts`, both `waitForSelector` (lines 32-108) and `waitForSelectorRemoval` (lines 114-190) have a TOCTOU race condition:

1. Initial `document.querySelector(selector)` returns null/truthy (lines 46/126)
2. Various setup code runs (callbacks, timer, abort listener)
3. `observer.observe(document.documentElement, ...)` is called (lines 102/184)

Between steps 1 and 3, DOM mutations can add/remove the target element. The MutationObserver misses these because it wasn't observing yet. The observer callback re-queries on *subsequent* mutations, but if no more mutations occur after the element appears, the promise hangs until timeout.

## Fix

After the `observer.observe()` call on line 102 (waitForSelector) and line 184 (waitForSelectorRemoval), add a re-check:

**waitForSelector (after line 106, before the closing `});`):**
```typescript
// Re-check after observe to close the TOCTOU race window
if (!settled) {
  try {
    const el = document.querySelector(selector);
    if (el) {
      settled = true;
      clearTimeout(timer);
      signal?.removeEventListener('abort', onAbort);
      observer.disconnect();
      resolve(el as T);
    }
  } catch {
    // querySelector errors are handled by the observer callback
  }
}
```

**waitForSelectorRemoval (after line 188, before the closing `});`):**
```typescript
// Re-check after observe to close the TOCTOU race window
if (!settled) {
  try {
    const el = document.querySelector(selector);
    if (!el) {
      settled = true;
      clearTimeout(timer);
      signal?.removeEventListener('abort', onAbort);
      observer.disconnect();
      resolve();
    }
  } catch {
    // querySelector errors are handled by the observer callback
  }
}
```

## Test approach

In `platform/plugin-sdk/src/dom.test.ts`, add tests that mock `document.querySelector` to return null on the first call (triggering observer setup) and then return the element on the second call (simulating the race). The promise should resolve without needing a DOM mutation to trigger the observer callback.

For waitForSelectorRemoval, mock querySelector to return an element on the first call, then null on the second call.

These tests verify the re-check path, not the observer path (which existing tests already cover).
